		  <p>Most needed are those ‘third places’ which lend a public balance to the increased privatization of home life. Third places are nothing more than informal public gathering places. The phrase ‘third places’ derives from considering our homes to be the ‘first’ places in our lives, and our work places the ‘second.’ </p>
		  <p>– Ray Oldenburg, from  the book <cite>The Great Good Place</cite>, 1989, © Ray Oldenburg</p>
		</div>
	  